        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>209</citedRange> (diplomatic transcription from Cherstich's thesis)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>121200</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.22</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Προκλῆς">Προκλῆς</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Στράτων">Στράτωνος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Proklès fils de Stratôn.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Prokles son of Straton.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Prokles figlio di Straton.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Neither Prokles nor Straton are rare names, the latter being quite common in Cyrenaica. No prosopographical link may be established.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
